# Guard `setState` in widget callbacks

Any `setState()` reachable from a callback passed to a child widget, controller, or listener **must** be preceded by `if (!mounted) return;`.

This includes synchronous callbacks — not just `async`, `Timer`, or `Future.delayed` paths.

## Why synchronous callbacks are dangerous

A child widget using `AutomaticKeepAliveClientMixin`, `GlobalKey` reparenting, or living inside a `TabBarView` can outlive its parent. The parent's callback closure still captures `this`, so the child can fire it after the parent is disposed.

## Rules

1. Every `setState()` inside a callback passed to a child widget or controller must have a `mounted` guard.
2. When a callback both calls `setState()` and forwards to a parent callback, guard **before** both — do not forward to a disposed widget's parent either.
3. Listener callbacks registered via `addListener` must check `mounted` before calling `setState`.

## Example

```dart
// BAD — crashes if parent is disposed while child is kept alive
void _onPositionChanged(Position position) {
  setState(() => _currentFen = position.fen);
  widget.onPositionChanged?.call(position);
}

// GOOD
void _onPositionChanged(Position position) {
  if (!mounted) return;
  setState(() => _currentFen = position.fen);
  widget.onPositionChanged?.call(position);
}
```
